# Python Development Rules

## Virtual Environment Requirements
- ALWAYS use python3 instead of python
- ALWAYS use pip3 instead of pip
- ALWAYS work within a Python virtual environment (venv)
- If no virtual environment exists, create one first using: python3 -m venv venv
- ALWAYS activate the virtual environment before any Python operations: source venv/bin/activate (on macOS/Linux) or venv\Scripts\activate (on Windows)

## Package Management
- Install packages using: pip3 install <package_name>
- Generate requirements using: pip3 freeze > requirements.txt
- Install from requirements using: pip3 install -r requirements.txt
- Never install packages globally - only within the activated virtual environment

## Python Execution
- Run Python scripts using: venv/bin/python3 -m script_name (without .py extension)
- Alternative: python3 script_name.py (but only after activating venv)
- Use python3 for all Python commands and scripts
- Prefer direct venv execution over activating venv each time

## Project Setup
- When setting up a new Python project:
  1. Create virtual environment: python3 -m venv venv
  2. Install required packages: venv/bin/pip3 install -r requirements.txt (if exists)
  3. Run the project: venv/bin/python3 -m main
- Alternative approach (if preferred):
  2. Activate environment: source venv/bin/activate
  3. Install required packages: pip3 install -r requirements.txt
  4. Run the project: python3 main.py

## Terminal Commands
- Prefer using venv/bin/python3 and venv/bin/pip3 directly instead of activating
- Use python3 and pip3 in all command suggestions and examples
- If activation needed: source venv/bin/activate (look for (venv) in prompt)

## Error Handling
- If import errors occur, first check if virtual environment is activated
- If packages are missing, install them using pip3 within the active venv
- Never suggest using sudo with pip installations 